name: scljet-sql-create-table
description: SclJet SQL CREATE TABLE — append a table's schema row + empty root, then INSERT/SELECT on it (matches reference sqlite3)
backends: [int, js]
---

# SclJet SQL CREATE TABLE

`CREATE TABLE t(col type, …)` appends the table's `sqlite_schema` row to page 1 and allocates an
empty table root page (the SQL text is stored verbatim). The new table then takes rows via INSERT
and answers SELECT. Verified out-of-band against reference sqlite3: `integrity_check` ok, `.schema`
shows both tables with the exact SQL, and the data matches sqlite running the same statements.
Locked here across backends.

[ByteSlice, SqliteValue, SqlInteger, SqlText, buildTableDatabase](std/scljet/index.ssc)
[queryImage, renderRows, executeMutation](std/scljet/sql.ssc)

```scalascript
def apply(db: ByteSlice, sql: String): ByteSlice =
  executeMutation(db, sql) match
    case Left(m) =>
      println(sql + " => ERR:" + m)
      db
    case Right(next) => next

def show(db: ByteSlice, sql: String): Unit =
  queryImage(db, sql) match
    case Left(m) => println(sql + " => ERR:" + m)
    case Right(rows) => println(sql + " => " + renderRows(rows).toString)

buildTableDatabase(512, 1, 1, "t", "CREATE TABLE t(id INTEGER, name TEXT)",
  List(List(SqlInteger(1L), SqlText("a")),
       List(SqlInteger(2L), SqlText("b")))) match
  case Left(error) => println("build-error:" + error.message)
  case Right(db0) =>
    val db1 = apply(db0, "CREATE TABLE t2(a INTEGER, b TEXT, c INTEGER)")
    val db2 = apply(db1, "INSERT INTO t2 VALUES (10, 'x', 100)")
    val db3 = apply(db2, "INSERT INTO t2 (b, a) VALUES ('y', 20)")
    val db4 = apply(db3, "CREATE TABLE t3(k INTEGER)")
    val db5 = apply(db4, "INSERT INTO t3 VALUES (7)")
    show(db5, "SELECT * FROM t")
    show(db5, "SELECT * FROM t2 ORDER BY a")
    show(db5, "SELECT a, c FROM t2 WHERE a >= 20")
    show(db5, "SELECT COUNT(*) FROM t2")
    show(db5, "SELECT * FROM t3")
```
